{"type":"message","id":"d2359f72","parentId":"0d5e9084","timestamp":"2026-03-07T02:33:43.874Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the full picture. \n\nThe `openclaw.json` config has memory paths defined as:\n- `workspace` → `/Users/aiagnet/.openclaw/workspace`\n- `memory-dir` → `/Users/aiagnet/.openclaw/workspace/memory`\n\nOpenClaw uses these names with a suffix `-main` (for the main agent), so it expects:\n- `workspace-main`\n- `memory-dir-main`\n\nBut the QMD index.yml has collections named:\n- `memory-root-main` \n- `memory-alt-main`\n- `memory-dir-main`\n\n\n- `workspace-main`\n\nSo `memory-dir-main` is actually in the index.yml, but the error shows `Collection not found: memory-dir-main-2`. That `-2` suffix is the real problem—it seems OpenClaw is appending a version or session number that doesn't exist in the actual collections. When I check what `qmd collection list` actually returns, it shows `workspace` and `memory`, which don't match the index.yml names at all.\n\nThis suggests the QMD index.yml is configuration for a specific agent instance, but `qmd collection list` is querying a different QMD setup entirely—possibly a global one. The `-2` suffix in the error might indicate a second session or instance trying to access a collection that doesn't exist in that context. something. Actually, looking at it again - in memory_search, the error mentions `memory-dir-main-2`. This might be how OpenClaw names collections when there are multiple agents or sessions.\n\nActually, wait. The QMD config file is at `/Users/aiagnet/.openclaw/agents/main/qmd/xdg-config/qmd/index.yml`. This is an agent-specific QMD config. The collections defined there are:\n- `memory-root-main`\n- `memory-alt-main`  \n- `memory-dir-main`\n- `workspace-main`\n\nBut when I run `qmd collection list`, it shows `workspace` and `memory`. This means the `qmd` command is using a DIFFERENT config/index than what OpenClaw's agent is using!\n\nThe `qmd` CLI uses the default XDG config location while OpenClaw's agent points to its own custom config directory. So when I list collections via the CLI, I'm seeing the global qmd config, not the agent-specific one with those differently-named collections. The `-2` suffix on `memory-dir-main-2` is puzzling - it doesn't match any collection name in the agent's index, so OpenClaw might be generating or appending that dynamically somehow. The agent-specific qmd index has the correct collection names in its config, but those collections might not actually be initialized in that instance, while the global qmd uses different names without the agent suffix. I should run qmd with the agent-specific configuration to see what's actually indexed there and check if there's a cache or index file I'm missing.","thinkingSignature":""},{"type":"toolCall","id":"toolu_01EQ2F5Zwqs2NmH9TL1Q4xg9","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"XDG_CONFIG_HOME=/Users/aiagnet/.openclaw/agents/main/qmd/xdg-config qmd collection list 2>&1"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"toolu_01LmZYPc1QGfXzRcjJ4wFJga","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls /Users/aiagnet/.openclaw/agents/main/qmd/ 2>&1"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"anthropic","model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","usage":{"input":1,"output":1358,"cacheRead":20983,"cacheWrite":1418,"totalTokens":23760,"cost":{"input":0.000003,"output":0.02037,"cacheRead":0.0062949,"cacheWrite":0.0053175,"total":0.0319854}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1772850797925}}
